<h2>What Counts as Content Marketing?</h2>
<p>Content marketing is the practice of publishing media that attracts and retains an audience without directly selling to them. The format does not matter. The intent does.</p>
<p>A blog post about HVAC maintenance is content marketing. A 30-second TV ad for the same HVAC company is not. The blog post earns attention by being useful. The ad rents attention by paying for placement.</p>
<p>The four pillars of content marketing are educate, engage, inspire, and entertain. Every example in this guide does at least one of those four jobs. The best examples do two or three at the same time.</p>
<p>Content marketing works because buyers research before they buy. Research from the <a href="https://contentmarketinginstitute.com/b2b-research/b2b-content-marketing-trends-research">Content Marketing Institute</a> shows 71% of B2B buyers consume blog content during their journey. Most content marketing fails because brands write for themselves instead of for that buyer.</p>
